{
  "schema_name": "eywa_node_response",
  "schema_version": "v1",
  "orchestration_decision": "delegate",
  "decision_notes": "The problem requires a balance between information gathering (probing) and cost minimization. I will split this into a mathematical strategy agent and an implementation agent.",
  "helpers": [
    {
      "label": "strategy_designer",
      "instructions": "Design an optimal probing strategy for the Polyomino Mining problem. The goal is to identify the locations of hidden polyomino shapes on a grid while minimizing the cost of queries. Consider the difference between single-cell queries (q 1) and multi-cell noisy aggregate queries (q k). Propose a method to use aggregate queries to narrow down potential locations of polyominoes and a method to verify them. The strategy should account for the fact that shapes are known but positions are not. Suggest a sequence of steps: initial coarse-grained sampling, refinement of candidate regions, and final verification."
    },
    {
      "label": "implementation_engineer",
      "instructions": "Implement the main.py script based on the provided problem description and the strategy provided by the strategy_designer. The script must: 1. Read the initial grid size, number of oil fields, noise parameter, and polyomino shapes from stdin. 2. Implement an interactive loop that uses stdout to send queries (q 1 or q k) and reads responses from stdin. 3. Use the strategy to decide which cells or groups of cells to query. 4. Finally, output the identified oil cells using the 'a k x1 y1 ... xk yk' format. Ensure the code handles standard input/output correctly, flushes stdout after every command, and follows the strict output contract. Use a robust baseline approach if the strategy is complex."
    }
  ],
  "synthesis_brief": "Combine the mathematical strategy (sampling and refinement logic) with the Python implementation template to produce a complete, functional main.py that minimizes probing cost while correctly identifying the oil cells."
}

